07:31.618 --> 07:34.371
and they can take breaks,
and they need one typewriter.

07:34.371 --> 07:36.582
They'll poop out that poem in ten minutes.

07:36.582 --> 07:38.917
Come on.
- No, drinks first. Come on.

07:38.917 --> 07:40.127
I can't believe

07:40.252 --> 07:42.629
that was just your first poem
published in <i>The Atlantic.</i>

07:42.629 --> 07:45.090
- Wonderful.
- And such specificity.

07:45.090 --> 07:46.967
Do you write with a pen or a scalpel?

07:46.967 --> 07:48.844
Oh, please.

07:48.844 --> 07:50.888
You all honor me, truly.

07:50.888 --> 07:52.890
Honestly, I don't know what comes next.

07:52.890 --> 07:56.685
I'm just trying to slurp the marrow
from the present moment.

07:56.685 --> 07:58.187
Poet laureate, 5:00.
Dr. Grillo!

07:58.187 --> 07:59.354
What?

07:59.479 --> 08:02.107
Ms. DuBois, when I read your poem
in <i>The Atlantic,</i>

08:02.107 --> 08:03.817
I revisited your book of sonnets.

08:03.817 --> 08:07.029
I've added it to the syllabus
for my spring seminar.

08:07.029 --> 08:09.489
I'm collecting selected poems

08:09.907 --> 08:12.492
for an anthology of contemporary poets

08:12.492 --> 08:14.244
re-imagining traditional forms.

08:14.244 --> 08:17.414
I would love to include
a villanelle of yours.

08:17.414 --> 08:18.957
Let's get a drink later.

08:18.957 --> 08:20.918
I would love that. I would...

08:25.047 --> 08:27.674
